Date: 9 May 2001
From: Matias Sacls <msacla@yahoo.com
Source: Associated Press, 8 May 2001 [edited
<http://news.excite.com/news/ap/010508/21/int-brazil-foot-and-mouth>

On Tuesday, government officials urged ranchers in southern Brazil to
slaughter thousands of cattle after 11 cases of highly contagious
foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) were discovered over the weekend.
Officials were already planning to vaccinate millions of cattle in the
region, near the border with Uruguay and Argentina. Now they're asking
farms in a 2-mile radius of the ranch where the disease was discovered to
kill and incinerate their animals.
"We are trying to convince ranchers in and around the affected area to
slaughter their herds," an Agriculture Ministry official said on condition
of anonymity. He said thousands of cattle could be slaughtered, but did not
have an exact number.
If the farmers refuse the slaughter proposal, then their animals would be
included among those to be vaccinated, the official said.
The disease has infected 11 cows near the border with Uruguay, which is
battling an outbreak of the disease. The affected ranch is located about
740 miles southwest of Sao Paulo in the state of Rio Grande do Sul.
Both the slaughter and the vaccine program are aimed at preventing the
spread of the disease to other areas of Brazil, which has one of the
largest commercial cattle herds in the world, with 160 million head.
--
