[2
Date: 9 May 2001
From: Matias Scala <msacla@yahoo.com>
Source: Reuters, 9 May 2001 [edited
<http://news.excite.com/news/r/010509/10/food-brazil-disease>

Brazil's southern ranching circuit may have a second case of foot-and-mouth
disease (FMD) on its hands only days after the first outbreak was confirmed
in Rio Grande do Sul, the state Agriculture Secretariat said.
A small but as yet unknown number of cattle in the town of Alegrete in Rio
Grande do Sul's interior showed signs associated with the disease.
"Field examination could not confirm it was FMD. The cattle had sores
around their mouths, but it could be a vesicular disease with similar
symptoms to foot-and-mouth," said a spokesman at the Agriculture Secretariat.
"The Agriculture Ministry's laboratory will examine blood samples taken
from the cattle. So far, we have not taken a containment policy on the
area. It is likely to be a couple days before we know the results."
Brazil's southernmost prime ranching state suffered its first outbreak in
over 10 months on Sunday when 11 cattle in Santana do Livramento, 3 km from
the border with Uruguay, were confirmed to have FMD.
Brazil -- pasture to the world's largest herd of 167 million head -- has
been scrambling to vaccinate its Rio Grande do Sul border with Uruguay and
Argentina, both of which have been in the grips of their own recent
multiple outbreaks of the virus.
